ğŸ”¹ VLOOKUP (Vertical Lookup)
ğŸ“Œ What is VLOOKUP?

VLOOKUP is used to search a value in the first column of a table and return a related value from another column in the same row.

ğŸ‘‰ It searches vertically (top to bottom).

ğŸ“Œ Syntax
=VLOOKUP(lookup_value, table_array, col_index_num, range_lookup)
small example for reference writing below 
=VLOOKUP("AUS".drag the table array,which column answer there that column number write accrding how you drag,if you write true it will also find approximate one (NOT FREATER THAN ONLY LESS THAN) OR (False means exact match)

ğŸ“Œ Example Table
ID	Name	Marks
1	   Ali	 85
2	  Sara	 90
3	  Tom	   78
ğŸ“Œ Example 1: Exact Match

Find Marks of ID 2

=VLOOKUP(2, A2:C4, 3, FALSE)


âœ” Output: 90

Explanation:

2 â†’ value to find

A2:C4 â†’ table

3 â†’ Marks column

FALSE â†’ exact match

ğŸ“Œ Example 2: Approximate Match (Grades)
Marks From	Grade
0	             F
50	           D
60	           C
70	           B
80	           A
=VLOOKUP(75, A2:B6, 2, TRUE)


âœ” Output: B

ğŸ“Œ Reason: Excel takes largest value â‰¤ 75, which is 70.

âš ï¸ Limitations of VLOOKUP

Lookup value must be in first column

Can only search left â†’ right

Column number is fixed (can break if columns move)
